It looks like older thrift client treats `isSet` for a variable differently (default value is considered as true for `isSet`) than newer version. But in Hive test mode, client and server version should be matched, so once it finds a variable (operation type?) is set, but the value is `DataOperationType.UNSET`, it means the value is not set properly so it will throw an exception. But in our case, the reason doesn't apply.

